Text: That's far enough, orc! Dismount and submit or die!
Text1: That's far enough, orc! Dismount and submit or die!
Out of our way, fools!

Text: Loss of life unavoidable.
I do what I must.
You are out of time.

Perhaps it is your imperfections... that which grants you free will... that allows you to persevere against all cosmically calculated odds. You prevail where the Titan's own perfect creations have failed.

Text1: Captain! Shipwreck off the starboard bow! There appear to be survivors!

Text: Now get your minds right! We'll be killing orcs within the hour.
Fall in!
That island on the horizon is our destination.
It's where we will do our duty, for our king, for Stormwind and for her people...
Hellscream has sent his best to take this island. We shall see to it that none return home...
Stormwind shall never fall!

Text1: Go, my naga! Welcome the mighty Tidehunter to Azeroth!

Text: You and your scaly worms are no match for me...

Text1: You fool! This day shall be your last!

Text: You've reached too far, serpent. You shall suffer greatly for your trespass!

Text1: To me, my minions! Strike now!
Now! Unleash the kraken!

Text: Aaaaaahhh...

Text1: Follow me, my pets! The realm of the mighty Neptulon is ours at last!

Text: What now, old friend?
We have suffered a tragic defeat.
Any hope for the future of our world has grown much bleaker.
Thrall must be told of this day's events.
He will guide our next steps...
Erunak! Noooo!
Graaaahahhhh!

Text1: You were a true man of the people, Liam.  Unlike any Royal I ever met.  We'll make them pay for this.

Text: Well, shaman, what now?
Erunak! Behind you!
May the Light bless the spirits of our ancestors, for they've chosen to allow my son to rest upon this holy ground.
It is here, surrounded by the heroes and patriots of Gilneas where he belongs.
We'll return, Liam.  I swear this to you.
Gilneas will remember your courage forever, Liam.
I apologize for the deception, but it was necessary.
In thousands of years, we have never seen one of your kind.
It was imperative that I first measure the bearing of your heart.
Come ride with me, little one. There is something I wish you to see.
We're gonna turn this place into a sinkhole, heh.
[NOTE: Many placeholder visuals in this cinematic. Expecting Observatory WMO & charge up visuals.]
Run, slicky! I dook up your like fer breakfast!
I am Anduin Wrynn, Prince of Stormwind. I won't die here. Not like this!
For Pandaria!

Text1: It's working! The wound is closing!
We risked everything, but we did it. Shen-zin Su will be okay.

Text: Our story begins long ago in the days of the monstrous Emperor Tian.
The Emperor was in need of trusted messengers and deliverymen.
So he took a strange, diminutive cave creature he found and warped it with the powers of the Vale.
What he created, was the "grummle."
Let us talk about the nature of power. In my hands I hold a sword. I ask you: Who wields the power?
I do, for I wield the sword!
A grummle can carry five times their own weight. They never sweat. They have an outstanding sense of smell.
And their skulls are harder than granite. Curiously, they all appear to be related.
Ancient Pandaren heroes freed the grummles from slavery.
The Yaungol warlord shows his face! Come, let's finish this!
Today they still act as traders, messengers, guides, and pack bearers for expeditions high up in Kun-Lai summit.
They are a very superstitious people, who often take on the names of their favorite charms, or "Luckydos."
The grummle suspicious of any luck they cannot smell, so it behooves one to meet new grummles with a pocketful of dung.
A very strange race, indeed.
Many thousands of years ago, the mogu held all the power. They ruled this land with fists of iron. But as their empire grew, they needed a way to police and control it.

They used the powers of the Vale, and their own flesh-warping magics, to twist and shape a race of ferocious lizards into a living weapon. They created an army. An army of Saurok. Bloodthirsty savages created to enforce the will of the emperor.
Ah, but there is a problem with creating a living weapon. Do you see?
Who, now, wields the power?
The heartless saurok, even with their tiny lizard brains, soon realized the truth of their position. They killed the enemies of the mogu.
Then they killed the subjects of the mogu.
Soon, they started killing the mogu themselves.
The mogu emperor then ordered all of the saurok to be purged. He tried to wipe out their entire race, to no avail. They still plague Pandaria to this day.
So you see - power is easily taken, but should not be lightly given.

Text1: Ready when you are, $p.
Come $p, let me show you.
Look through the spyglass.
The Sha of Hatred is inside that mantid structure... I suspect it was drawn to a powerful host there.
To get in, we will need specially tuned crystals from some of the mantid leaders in the area.
I located these leaders here...
here...
and here.
Kill them.  Take the crystals.  Should be simple enough.

Text: My, my. Hello, stranger! Sampled my dream brew, have we? Its visions are hard to interpret - half truth, half illusion. Who's to say which is which?
What the...?
What was that noise?
It came from the wall, sir.
I know where it CAME from, what was it?
No... no...
Men! To arms!
You three! $n! Assist Captain Oakenshield in the front!
Greentill! Blacksoil! Cover our left flank! I don't want any surprises!
Leven, take the right side! You're on your own!
Everyone else! If you can hold a weapon, protect the village! Don't let them past this line! You...
We don't stand a chance...
Everyone, fall back! FALL BA-
Rrrraaaa!!!
Who are you?
Does it matter who we are? We are here to help you.
Hey! Gimme one o' them pitchforks!
You were surrendering? Why? Because these invaders can break down a wall?
You have got another wall... and it's made up of the people who call this place HOME.
Any one of us would lay down our life to protect this land.
This land, it belongs to us...
It belongs to our ancestors...
It belongs to our children.
And we are not about to let that change.
You are too late! The Thunder King will rise and take dis land from you.
How did they find us? Ready your weapons - we've got to get out of this canyon!
Oh... I seem to have lost my sword.
When the Sundering ripped apart the continents of Azeroth, we pandaren thought that the rest of the world had been utterly destroyed.
But as the centuries passed, one young explorer decided to see what was out there. His name was Liu Lang. And he set out to discover the world... on the back of a turtle!
We celebrate his bravery with statue and song, but if you were actually there on the beach that very day - well, I'm sure he looked quite silly, indeed.

Oh, how the pandaren laughed at him. But Liu Lang was more clever than anyone thought. Sea turtles always return to the beach where they were born. And so, despite the mists that envelop our land, he always had a way home.
Every few years, he returned - with tales of mysterious cities in the sand, nomadic people living on endless grassy plains, a great empire under the ice, and a magical kingdom gilded in gold.
Each time he returned, more and more pandaren answered Liu Lang's call, and joined him on his growing turtle. They were the bravest among us: The explorers. The adventurers.
And that is the lesson of Liu Lang, my friend. Everyone always laughs at the explorer. They always laugh... until he returns.
Great events often have humble beginnings. Consider: a quiet pond. Still. The water is like a sheet of glass.
Until I throw a stone. Such a small thing - but soon, ripples engulf the whole of the lake!
The jinyu also have humble origins. Once primitive creatures, they were fortunate enough to live near the enchanted pools within the Vale.
The magic of the pools expanded their minds and grew their bodies, until they became one of the great ancient cultures of Pandaria.
The wisest of the jinyu are very wise indeed - they can speak to the rivers the way you and I would consult our elders.
In the whispering waters, they can hear the future.
The jinyu and their waterspeakers stand at the very heart of the greatest events in Pandaria's history.
Their visions built empires, freed slaves, and warned our Last Emperor of the Sundering that shattered Azeroth ten thousand years ago.
Think about it: the smallest voice can change the world. Consider that, friend, the next time you decide to start throwing stones!
Oh, my student - you wish to study the mantid? Be warned: the pandaren frontier is littered with the graves of former pupils.
The mantid are harsh teachers.

Every generation, the mantid swarm the Serpent's Spine wall in great numbers. They murder many pandaren, so we kill many times their number in return. Yet each generation, they attack once more. Why do they do this?
We pandaren do not know.
Our ancient writings indicate that the mantid have always been here. They predate even the mogu. Where did they come from?
We pandaren do not know.
Perhaps, if you were to befriend the mantid, and earn a reputation among them, they would teach you their secrets. But I warn you:
Nobody has ever befriended the mantid.

Here is what the pandaren do know: By massacring our people, by slaughtering tens of thousands of pandaren, generation after generation, they have taught us the value of life. A precious but fleeting gift. Easily snuffed out... in an instant.
This is what the mantid have taught us.
What do you fear most in this world? Have you conquered your fear... or has your fear conquered you?
In the ancient days before the sundering of the world, the mogu emperors ruled over Pandaria. My people were made slaves, and they were afraid.
The mogu were masters of pain and torture, of dark magics and brutal weapons. No pandaren, hozen, or jinyu could resist the power they held. And my people were afraid.
It was the mogu who built the Serpent's Spine. The most unlucky of slaves were sent to aid in its construction and defense, to be fodder for the mantid. And my people were afraid.
As the empire grew, the mogu began to experiment with the secrets of the Vale. They crafted terrible weapons of living flesh and stone. And my people were afraid.
In their hubris, the mogu never foresaw that their downfall lay in wait, not among their enemies, but among the oppressed. The day that one slave stood...
...and was no longer afraid.

Fire! It is the most magical of elements. It warms us, it cooks our food. It is the hearthfire that makes a house a home. In the right hands, fire can shape iron into swords or plowshares. Left uncontrolled, fire could destroy a city.
Fire is the instrument of change.

Long ago, a group of sturdy nomad hunters wandered the world. By a stroke of fate, they were here in Pandaria when the Sundering split apart the continents of Azeroth. The wanderers found themselves trapped in the Townlong Steppes, a harsh and dangerous land.

Those noble hunters found a way to survive on their own. Fire was the key. They drew up oil from the ground. They used it to heat their homes, cook their food, and burn their enemies. They grew STRONG.
From the flames of fate, the yaungol were born. They survive beyond the wall, for they refuse to submit to any law but their own.
Has fate been cruel to the yaungol? You may as well ask if fire is good or bad.
Fate is like fire; it can shape or destroy us.
All that matters is what you do with it.

Ah! You wish to learn of our last and greatest emperor, Shaohao? My friend, I do not have the time here to recount all of his adventures, but his actions ten thousand years ago resonate to this very day.

We know that he purged his doubts in the Jade Forest. That he cleansed himself of despair in the Krasarang Wilds. That he overcame his fear in Townlong Steppes. And that he defeated anger, hatred, and violence high in the mountains of Kun-Lai.
This is known; and there are temples to mark these most sacred of places.

But I want you to imagine standing in this very valley on the day he returned from his journey. Imagine being here when the gates opened for him. By then our emperor was a creature of pure light: No doubts, no fears, no hatred...
It is said that all the trees in the vale blossomed as he entered, and continue to blossom to this day.

Would that we could all live like our most sacred emperor. That we could put aside all our burdens and exist in harmony with the cosmos. THAT, I believe, was his message to us... before he became one with the land, and hid Pandaria away from the terror of the Sundering.
Thank you, dear emperor.
One day, a father grew tired of his young cub's misbehavior.  "You act just like a hozen!" the father scolded. Still, his son misbehaved.
To teach him a lesson, the father dragged the cub out to the forest, to watch how the hozen live. "Do you see what the hozen are like?" he asked. "Do you want to live like that?"
The hozen are quite lively indeed. A short-lived race, few hozen survive past their 20th birthday. Their leaders are all 14 or 15. How mature were you at 14 years old? Meditate on that!
Afterwards, the father asked his cub what he had learned.

"I learned that we work and toil on our little farm, but that the hozen have the whole world as their garden," the cub said. "I learned that we squint by the light of a single candle, but that the hozen enjoy the light of the stars. I learned that I go to school every day, but that the hozen learn by doing."
And the cub concluded, "I should very much like to live like a hozen!"
Who then, was the wiser? The father or the cub?
That, my friend, is for you to decide.
Think you can take me in battle?  Most girls hate snakes, but I think they're cute!
Text1: Think you can take me in battle?  Most girls hate snakes, but I think they're cute!

Text: Ah, if it isn't my favorite master assassin! I was hoping I would find you here in Pandaria.
Very good. Let's talk.
Tong! Drinks, please.
My father, Deathwing, tried to destroy the whole of Azeroth.
He was misguided, of course, but he was right about one thing: Our world is... so fragile.
We are a point of light in a universe of shadow. A candle in a tempest.
Sometimes I think it was the very precariousness of our world that drove my father to madness.
Ah, thank you Tong.
Now, to my point: I believe we are headed towards a reckoning. And no, I am not talking about the current conflict between the Alliance and the Horde.
Believe me - what Garrosh Hellscream achieved in Theramore is nothing compared to the horrors that are even now bearing down on our fragile home.
But the war deeply troubles me. Do you see my concern?
A divided Azeroth cannot possibly stand against the darkness.
This war has to end. Soon. Before it consumes our strength!
I want you to know that your Alliance has my full and unwavering support in this campaign.
You can rest assured that my loyalties lie with your Horde.
How do we bring a swift and decisive end to the conflict? I believe the answer lies with heroes like you.
We must ensure that you are up to the task... and then equip you accordingly.
Two hundred ships at my disposal, yet the one carrying my SON goes missing!
I am sorry, but I cannot go back just yet.
I've decided to search for the Vale... Vale... Vale...
STORM the shores, and PAINT THIS NEW CONTINENT RED!!
Ah, another stranger from beyond the mists.

Ten thousand years ago, the last Pandaren Emperor came seeking my advice. He, too, was filled with conflict. Let us see if you are correct, Taran. Let us see how this stranger deals with turmoil of the soul.
We can agree it is noble to fight for a righteous cause: to defend home or family. But what of vengeance? What of anger? I sense these emotions run deep in this one.

Well spoken, Zhi. The strangers from beyond the mists have no shortage of passions, but let us see if they indeed control them. Beyond anger lies hatred, the wellspring of all misery. What is this? Your hatred has a face!

This one has indeed proven mastery over anger. Between the young cub's words and the actions of this hero, I think I understand. Those from beyond the mists are hardened by battle. They are scarred, yes, but they have learned much. I trust them.
It is decided. The Vale of Eternal Blossoms shall remain open. The transgressions of the outsiders have been great... but I see in them the capability to right what has been wronged.
I will consult the others. Meet me at the gates.
You are too late.
Da remains of da Thunder King were taken to da Isle of Reckoning.
We performed da ancient rites...
Even now, da true emperor of Pandaria lives and breathes once more.
Woe to da pandaren usurpers! The mogu will rule dis land again, and we Zandalari will have a new homeland...
Secure da remains, bruddahs!
Da Thunder King shall live again...
Under Kun-Lai Thunder sleeps...
The storm long spent there rests...
But blood of brother kingdom keeps...
Alive the dispossessed...
By Zandalari blood he will be taken...
To Zandalari voice he will awaken...

Text1: Children of Pandaria. The mists have fallen. For good or for ill, our land is open to all.
Let us draw ourselves together to rebuild this sacred place, the first step toward healing a war-torn world.

Text: I have faith in our friends from beyond the mists.
Their strength is an inspiration... and sorely needed. We must trust that their hearts are pure.
We've been flying in this mist for hours, General. The crew grows... uneasy.
Back to your post, soldier! We'll find this land, or die trying.
Alliance ship! Portside!
Attack!
Enemy ship, starboard! Ready the guns! Fire at will!
Direct hit! She's goin' down!
Land ho!
Uhh, somethin' ain't right, General... We're losin' altitude! Fast!
Thanks to your actions, the Hozen fear your people. Indulge me a moment...
Ah! Here we are. Over 14,000 years ago, this entire land was ruled by a terrible race of warlords called "the mogu."
The mogu ruled through fear. And fear kept them in power... until the first Pandaren monks taught my people courage.
Then the mogu were overthrown.
You see, those who lead through fear only stay in power while those they govern lack courage.
The hozen are many things, but they are not cowards - not for long. If you don't wish to fight them, you must... inspire them!
I will help you, but first I would like to learn a little more about your people. Will you journey with me for a little while?
What is the source of YOUR power? Think carefully before you answer. Many adventurers point to their weapons, or their equipment, or to tomes of arcane might.
Long ago, when my people were slaves of the mogu empire, we were forbidden from carrying any weapon at all. We were not fighters. And no one believed we could fight the mogu without magic and steel.
Until Kang, the Fist of First Dawn, opened our eyes.
One day, the beloved monk issued a challenge to his fellow slaves. "Hit me!" he called out.
Surprised, the beleaguered Pandaren slaves tried to strike Kang. One by one they failed, for he intercepted their blows like a dancer and sidestepped their attacks like a reed in the wind.

"Our backs are hardened by the whips of the mogu," he told them. "Our arms are powerful from building their fortresses. Our minds are sharp from working alongside our enemy. You think the mogu are stronger? I say we are their strength!"
The farmers, the bricklayers, the shepherds and the smiths... they all bowed before Kang. "Teach us," they said. "Teach us to fight."
And when they rose... they rose as warriors.
Your voice. Your hands. THESE are the tools of true heroes. Use them well... and you can change the world.
Hahahahaha!
Do you like my snakes? I get the feeling they don't like you!
Text1: Do you like my snakes? I get the feeling they don't like you!
Death to all who dare challenge my empire!

Text: <Roars.>
Nevermore!

Text1: Such is the fate of those who question authority.

Text: Do you have a few moments to spare?

Text1: My snakes are pretty right? ...RIGHT?
You never stood a chance against me and my lovely snakes!
No way! I will get you next time!
Try this guy on for size!
Take that!
Nooooo! My precious snakes!
I'm going to knock you out cold!
I told you, sugar. You aren't hot enough to handle me!
Ouch! I just got burned!
Take a break and chill, sweetie. You'll get your turn again soon.
We're snowballing out of control! You don't stand a chance now!
Shattered!
You handle the cold better than I thought.
Your pet is a cold, ruthless killer!
I won't let you get away with that!

Text: ...you're nothing but farmer's children.

Text1: Target acquired. Light it up.
Burn it to the ground!
Roger that. Give 'em the business.
We read you. Comin' in hot.
Carrier has arrived.
Nightwind, report! What's going on down there?
Horde troops are swimming toward your position. Open fire at once.
You don't think they'll hesitate to strangle you with their bare hands? GUN THEM DOWN!

Text: No sign of the flagship, and no sign of Admiral Taylor or Prince Anduin.
Admiral - I think they mean to surrender. They're not armed - They're just trying not to drown!
That's not right... this is a massacre... they were unarmed - ugh! I don't... I don't feel well...
Maybe they deserved to die.
You beasts! What sort of madness is this?
Men, stand down - this is one of the natives.
We are from the Alliance, and mean you no harm. Tell me, what was that shadow you drew out of me?
This is not the place to explain. In short, your own doubts have been made manifest, as a consequence of your actions.
You don't understand - we're fighting a war here-

Oh, I understand perfectly. I have eyes. But Pandaria is not like whatever land you came from; it lives and breathes. You should be careful what kind of energy you bring here. Now put those weapons away!
What is - no - NO! They had an airbase, a hidden airbase... my ship - my - Hellscream will have my head!
They all must die.
You! Bear-creature. What kind of sorcery was this?
We bring only our honor and the desire to crush our enemies. Have your kind been aiding the Alliance?
Stranger - your own doubts have been made manifest. Pandaria is not like whatever land you come from; it lives and breathes. You should be careful what kind of energy you bring here.
It is not our desire to get wrapped up in your bloodshed. Now have your men lower their weapons, or you will face TWO enemies on this continent.
Your doubts and hatreds have wrought havoc all throughout these ruins. Clean up after yourselves and meet me in the village below - I will do my best to explain.
You scum will NOT destroy this land as you defiled Kalimdor!
Coward!
What in blazes is this?
Admiral, we're seeing a significant native presence here. Ornate structures-
Cut the chatter, people. Eyes on the target!
Text1: Cut the chatter, people. Eyes on the target!

Text: You heard the admiral. Concentrate fire on the Horde base. Begin your attack runs.
They're firing on us sir!
Text1: They're firing on us sir!

Text: Use your torpedo rockets on those ships.
Confirmed kill. Nice shooting.
Well done. No mercy!
Text1: Well done. No mercy!

Text: That one's for Theramore!
Text1: That one's for Theramore!

Text: Any sign of the flagship down there?
Text1: Any sign of the flagship down there?

Text: Negative, Admiral. No sign of Captain Taylor OR his flagship.
Ugh! We've been hit!
Text1: Ugh! We've been hit!

Text: Heavy enemy fire... Sully, pull up!
We're not gonna make it! I'm comin' ta see you soon, pappy!
Pay 'em back! Hit them with everything you've got!
Text1: Pay 'em back! Hit them with everything you've got!

Text: That's enough - all wings, report back. Prepare for ground assault.
Text1: That's enough - all wings, report back. Prepare for ground assault.
The flagship's last reported position was below. Can you see anything?

Text: Fog... nothing but dense fog... wait! Land - starboard! I see ships.
After you, my good sir.
I say, it looks like I've racked up another win!
That is most unfortunate.
Ah, but were you expecting this?
It seems I'll be enjoying an expedient win this fine day!
Oh dear, I'm losing!
Now's as good a time as any, I suppose.
I knew I made the right choice when I took this up!
Maybe I can still get my old farm back...
I've found it sometimes helps to change things up a bit.
If only my wife were here to see this. I'm going to win!
There's plenty more where that came from!

Text1: I won't go easy on you!
In your face!
Mommy! Mommy! The mean tamer didn't let me win!
Oh no you don't!
Take that!
W-why did you k-kill my bunny...

Text: I do hope you're prepared to feed your pets to mine as a treat.
I did warn you of the dangers of these woods.
Your courage is impressive.
Do you feel something?
What a show!
No matter. A single life for a victory is well worth the sacrifice.
Avast, land lubbers be attackin'! Man the harpoons!
All the booty ish mine!
Why'd you go and have to do that? ...hic!
Give 'em hell!
Now that...that is fightin'! Whoever's controllin' these pets sure ish somethin'! ...hic!
Man down!
We be killin' you now.
Now that is what Zunta be talkin' about!
You be da victor today. Enjoy it.
How about you try dis one on for size?
Good, good. Zunta give you a treat later.
Why you so mean to Zunta, eh?

Text1: Battle is upon us. Crush them!
The day is ours.
I'll beat you soon enough.
I won't give you the pleasure.
Keep going! Kill!
Not important. I will stop at nothing to win!
Do not be fooled by my calmness. I will defeat you.
Victory is ours, children!
Well done. You've beaten me when few have had the luxury.
A surprising twist!
Success!
How could you?
You're gonna hurt like you never hurt before when I'm through with ya.
You feelin' da hurt, mon?
I never see nobody fight like you be fightin'.
I bet you never saw dis one comin'.
Look at da little one hurtin'!
Looks like dis one has a bit of a sting!
I'm warning you, I will not falter under your assault.
Fighting the strength of the land is inevitably futile.
You fight well.
The earth will never falter!
The cycle continues.
You fight against the unstoppable.

Text: We fight!
Me win!
NO! ME WIN!
No! No kill! Fight this one instead!
Good tiny thing! You kill other tiny thing!
Why you no fight? I said fight!

Text1: Let us begin.
Looks like I left you earthbound!
We've been shot out of the sky!
Great job. Take a break!
We just might win this!
A beautiful creature has fallen.
Activating aggression modules!
You never stood a chance against my augmented team!
Total system failure!
Engaging self-preservation chip.
No letting up. Full speed ahead!
That's nothing a good spit shine won't fix.

Text: You think I'm scared of you? I faced Onyxia!
Who's great? I am!
I hope a dragon eats you!
Alright, that's enough. Switch!
That's what happens when you go into the whelp pits!
I've been wiped out!
You cannot possibly comprehend the forces stacked against you.
Perhaps now you're ready to see things my way?
You only delay us. We cannot be stopped.
Have you ever seen such a magnificent being?

Text1: Those are Horde vessels... General quarters! Get our birds in the air. Clear the decks. Stations, people. Let's go to war!

Text: Give up now while you still have the chance!
A minor inconvenience.

Text1: This won't take long.

Text: None can stop the Grimtotem!

Text1: Your impudence will be your undoing. Mark my words!
This isn't over!
So weak.
You'll pay for that.

Text: Not to worry, I'll make this quick.
That wasn't so bad, was it?
Perhaps I need to increase the dosage to prevent such quick deaths.
Don't be so sure of yourself.
It won't be long now.
How unfortunate.

Text1: I'll show you firsthand the strength of undeath.
I knew I was stronger!
No...no...
Rest, my precious.
Yes...join us!
No! We will not be defeated!

Text: Are ye sure that ye want to face the might of dragons?
Now it's time to show my brother who the real master tamer is!
You got lucky. That's all.
That's enough!
Now that's what I'm talkin' about!
No! I just finished raising that one!

Text1: I hope you like losing!
I knew the swamp was the right choice!
Perhaps it was wrong of me to venture here.
The swamp conceals many things.
Victory shall be mine!
This is looking bleak for me.

Text: By the hammer of me father, I shall defeat ye!
That's the stuff, boys. We did it!
You won't be deterrin' me. Not today. I'll keep trainin'!
Try this'n on fer size!
Great job!
How dare ye...

Text1: I will show you no mercy.
Just as I thought. You never stood a chance.
Curse you!
I am far from finished.
That was too easy.
You'll suffer for your transgression.
I'm going to wreck you!
Now that's what I'm talking about! Woohoo!
Maybe I should've gone with more weapons...
Oh no you don't!
Bam!
Hey! I spent some serious gold on that!

Text: Don't go easy on me!
I bet if I keep winning, I'll get invited to fight in Stormwind one day!
Wow, you're really good!
Let's keep going!
Good job!
Oh no...
These creatures have suffered enough. I will not let you defeat them!
The spirits smile upon my victory!
Ancestors forgive me. I have failed...
Come rest. You will need your strength later in the battle.
Lok'tar!

Text: A bell cast from the makers' flesh, shaped by stars' fire, and bound by the breath of darkest shadow.
This bell, when rung, could shake the world and call to the heavens.
Taken to war, the bell's cacophonous tones stirred the hearts of Lei Shen's warriors.
It fueled their hatred and anger, lending them strength on the field of battle.
The bell's screaming voice struck fear and doubt into the hearts of the Emperor's enemies, sending them fleeing in his path.
Awed by its power, the Thunder King described the instrument as "the voice of the gods," and named it the Divine Bell.
Eventually, the Thunder King fell, and the Bell changed hands. Many tried to use its power. Some tried to silence its sound. All failed.
Finally, the Korune spellweavers laid claim to their instrument and hid it away. Since then, the Bell has been lost to history.

But the ookin' bell it was meant for could never be mine.
The mogu had stolen the bell, what is a hozen to do?
Think of the horror if those dookers stole the mallet too.
Mogu are not bright, they fail to see things for what they are.
The Monkey King broke the mallet and sent the pieces afar.
My Hozen took the pieces and scattered them across the lands,
Disguised as "nifty nibs", never to fall into mogu hands.
The head, the handle, these two must be made as one.
Combined with evil's ointment, the bell's evil can be undone.
If "Garrosh" has the bell than there is only one thing to do,
I'll send for my hozen friends, the mallet must be made anew.
Here goes nothing. My research did not have nice things to say about this Jade Warlord. Be ready for battle.
Let us begin.
You never stood a chance.
What?  How is this possible!
Let's give someone else a chance to do some damage!
Did you really think all of your pets would survive?
No!  That was my favorite pet!

Text1: My King, I promise you. The Kirin-Tor will come down on Garrosh so hard his ancestors will reel. Blood will pay for blood!

Text: Jaina -
I will end Garrosh for this. His Horde already crumbles beneath him. We will deliver the final blow.
Champion, you and Anduin thwarted the Warchief today and won the Alliance a critical victory.
But please, leave me now. I must tend to my son... and prepare for our next battle.
Alright, we have the handle, the head, and the ointment like you asked for. Can you re-assemble the mallet?
Ayup! Silly youngin, just put rod in hole. And the mallet shall again be whole.
Good as nibby new! But listen to the Monkey King. You only have enough ointment for one true swing.
Only one swing? Are we sure this will work? Is there any way to get more ointment?

The Monkey King was there, the last time this mallet struck true. Tears came to eyes, and harmony was felt through and through. But no more ointment was ever made, for the mogu came with their raid. Use what you have, be grateful it is there. For the bell is a dangerous weapon, so handle with care.
I will show no mercy!

Text1: The charges are placed. Hero - you may have the honor.

Text: The unworthy have not yet learned of my power.
War-God Al'chukla, add my strength to your own.
Make a demonstration of these invaders, such that all nations tremble before me.
All will fall before us!!
Shan Bu, secure the inner courtyard. None should look upon my works and live.
As my emperor wills!
My Lord.
It is said the God King Rastakhan, ruler of the Zandalari, lords over his mighty kingdom from a throne carved of solid gold.
Years ago, as he sat on this opulent seat of power, he was visited by his most trusted prophet: Zul.
Zul warned King Rastakhan of a terrible Cataclysm. For Zul had seen a vision of a great armored dragon clenching the world in his ferocious jaws.
King Rastakhan did nothing.
Months later Zul returned, bearing more grim news from his visions. He saw a legion of serpents pouring forth from a gaping fissure that tore open the floor of the ocean.
Still, King Rastakhan did nothing.
Finally, mere months before the Cataclysm, Zul returned. Tearing his clothes and throwing his staff to the ground, Zul spoke of earthquakes and tidal waves.
He described the golden capital of Zandalar slowly sinking beneath the waves in the aftermath of the Cataclysm, its once-great people drowning as their mighty works slipped forever beneath the sea.

King Rastakhan tired of Zul and his troubling nightmares. To be rid of the prophet, he granted Zul the use of his largest ships, so that he and his followers could seek a new land if his visions came to pass.
And his visions DID come to pass.

When Deathwing rose from the Maelstrom, dark, angry waves crashed into the Zandalari capital. The spine of the land broke in two, and soon, the city and all its riches began to slide into the hungry sea.

The Zandalari people turned to their King for help, but there was only one Zandalari equipped to help them: The prophet Zul. The prophet, and the mighty warfleet he had assembled while his King sat idle.
You see, the TRUE power of kings and emperors stems from the power to aid their people.
The moment they fail, they cede their power to the one who can.
The mogu tell a legend about Lei Shen, the Thunder King.
His followers fell to their knees before him. "We will call you 'The Lightning King,'" they said.
It is said that he tore out the very heart of the mogu God. And from that hateful act he gained power over wind and storm.
But Lei Shen did not agree.
"Lightning strikes in an instant and is over in a flash," he said.
"But thunder. Thunder! Thunder proclaims the coming of the storm."
"Thunder quakes the skies long before the lightning strikes, and thunder echoes in the hills long after lightning's power is spent."
"It is thunder that sends animals cowering and fills the hearts of peasants with dread. Let thunder be my herald, so that my power is felt throughout the land."
"I will be... The Thunder King."
Oh my friend - that awful sound. For a hundred hundred generations the crash of thunder filled the hearts of pandaren with terror.
It is said that after the revolution, the Red Crane of Hope placed the rainbow in the sky, so that pandaren would know not to fear the storms any longer.
I do not see any rainbows today. Do you?
Fathers and sons. Mothers and daughters. As parents, we pass our legacy on to our children.
What values do we choose to instill in our progeny?
What will our children learn from our mistakes?
What sort of world will we create and leave behind for our daughters and sons?
Parents place their children on a path, but they do not always know where the road will take them.
The mogu were children as well. Children of the titans. They were once a legion of stone, heartless and obedient.
By the titans' command, they fought the terrible servants of the old gods. They shaped the mountains and carved the rivers of the land.
And they created a magical cradle of life in a hidden valley that we now call the Vale of Eternal Blossoms.
But eventually the titans fell silent. And their creations were cursed with flesh.
The mogu grew restless. Many generations later, when Thunder King united them, they seized upon their legacy!
I truly believe now that the mogu thought they were doing the work of the titans. They fought against the mantid and used the powers of the Vale to create new life.
Ah, but such terrible works!
Parents cannot always be assured of the legacy they will leave behind.
How especially true this is, when the parents are gods. And their children - monsters.
Destroy them, me brothers!
The Thunder King! What a magnificent individual.
Could you imagine what his empire would be like today if it had not been overthrown and hidden by the pandaren?
I couldn't imagine a crueler tyrant. He enslaved this entire continent.
Benevolence is a luxury for the strong, young prince. No great empire was ever built with kindness.
...I'm not so sure about that. But I can tell you: no great empire has ever stood the test of time by crushing its own citizens.
Remember, the mogu were overthrown! THAT should be the lesson of the Thunder King. It's your move, by the way.
I worry you may be too soft to wear your kingdom's crown, Prince Anduin. You would do well to learn some of your father's hardness.
Are you lecturing me? You're what - two years old?
Two in DRAGON years. It is your move.
Hmmm.
...Why did you play that piece just now?
It's a Pandaren board game. The object is for both players to win.
That's ridiculous! Why would you even play!?
Champion, return now to the Isle of the Thunder King. I will meet you at the forge, where together we will create an instrument of legendary power.
To what end? What are you two working towards?
...world peace!
Using a mogu weapon forge whose powers you barely understand?
My dear prince, you and I share the same goals. We only differ in our level of commitment.
Come, hero! Let us shape a new Azeroth together!
Champion, I know that our people are at war, but if you blindly trust this black dragon in the pursuit of power, are you any better than your warchief? Please - just be careful.
My friend, if you blindly trust a black dragon in the search for greater power, are you any better than Garrosh Hellscream? Please - just be careful.
Tong, is that our friend?
I can't believe you're still alive.
Remind me to tell you the story about my friend here and what we accomplished together at Ravenholdt. Good times!
What did I tell you? Few mortals possess such courage and tenacity.
Meet me atop Mason's Folly, where we met before!
What are you two plotting?
I keep no secrets! You are welcome to accompany us, Anduin Wrynn. If your injury permits.
I implore my Horde friend here not to push you off of the cliff.
Truly a splendor! Have you ever seen such a view, Prince Anduin?
It's breathtaking.
It's about to get even more awe-inspiring.
Champion! Behold the fruits of your labors!
At the dawn of the world, when the mortal races were young, they did not yet possess the secrets of fire.
They shivered in the cold and the rain until - in one instant - lightning tore the sky!
It rent a tree asunder and set it aflame.
The mortals gathered around the fire in awe and wonder. It could cook their food and warm their homes. They seized it! And protected it!
They fed the fire every hour of every day. Hot coals were carried from one primitive camp to the next. Do you see? In a single flash of light, civilization was born.
Truly, lightning is a gift of the Gods.
The mogu, ah! The mogu! Their minds were so small! They were built to serve, and when they lost their masters, they served themselves.
But they could have been so much more.
They built an empire, when they could have built a new world.
We will do better, champion. Behold! The Crown of Heaven! My gift to you.
You are the ember. You are the spark! You are the fire that will spread across the world. You will awaken Azeroth's potential!
Come to me.
We know now that the mogu share their roots with the Titans. But many mysteries remain. Why were they here? Why Pandaria?
What were the mogu sent here to guard? Or destroy? We are missing the final puzzle pieces, and YOU will help me find them!
The crown I have given you will be as your third eye. It will tie us together. I will see what you see. Together we will lay the secrets of the Titans bare.
I will be watching you closely, hero!
Champion... I would think twice before putting that thing on your head.
According to this runestone, the mogu were Titan constructs, soulless creatures built of stone. We suspected as much.
You've found another stone! What have we learned? The "curse of flesh" made the mogu mortal. Ah - but later, they found a way to reverse the process. A clever race.
The mogu served a Titan keeper. His name was "Ra." In the mogu tongue, "Ra-den" means "Master Ra." Fascinating! I must know more!
According to this, the mogu and their master were sent to Pandaria. They were pursuing a great darkness - ah, the fragment is incomplete. We must find others.
Here, there is mention of an Old God. "Y'Shaarj." A beast with seven heads, who breathed darkness. I suspect that thing was the source of the sha that haunts Pandaria to this day.

This runestone speaks of a "Cradle of Life." A place where the Titans could create new creatures. Oh - of course - the Vale of Eternal Blossoms! It was a living laboratory, much like Un'goro Crater or Sholazar Basin.
We're beginning to put the pieces together, champion. The mogu were created and sent here to guard the Vale for their Titan masters. Guard it from what? Were the Old Gods still a threat?
Here, this fragment speaks of "The Winged Legions of Y'Shaarj." Servants of an Old God? Could this mean the mantid?
This runestone is more recent than the others. Something about "The sleeping keeper." I think it's referring to Ra-Den. But why was he asleep?

You've found another piece of the puzzle! This was carved by the mogu. They were frustrated - a thousand years with no orders from their master, and their bodies had turned to flesh. The mogu began to argue among themselves.

Hmmm. This runestone speaks of mogu savagery. They fell apart into warrior clans. But one King was more ambitious than the others - Lei Shen. The Thunder King. When the Titan Keeper fell silent, Lei Shen decided to speak for him.

Ah! The final piece of the puzzle. The Thunder King took on the powers of Ra-Den, the very essence of a Titan. He united the mogu into an empire and tried to continue the Titans' work. Of course he saw himself as a God!
Quickly, return to me at the Veiled Stair. We should talk face-to-face.
I have been looking forward to your return, champion.
The Thunder King took within himself the powers of a Titan keeper. We must take them back!
Bring me his cruel, black heart. We will be doing the Pandaren a favor, and the powers that we liberate will once again be put to the service of Azeroth.
A chill just went up my spine!
Something tells me our friend has returned triumphant.
Ahhh - the heart of a King. The powers of a God.
What are you doing? You're not seriously going to eat that-
It is filled with Titan magic, the very language of creation...
Oh - I see them - a million, million worlds - glittering in their perfection - but one above all others - oh -
WE HAVE FALLEN. WE MUST REBUILD THE FINAL TITAN. DO NOT FORGET.
What are you trying to pull?
It is gone. I don't remember any of it. Oh! None of them remember. The irony!
What are you talking about? I don't trust you.
You are wise not to.
Champion, I need time to... "digest" what I have learned.  But soon, we will take action.
Good to see you again adventurer.  Are you ready to begin?
Let's go!
Text1: Let's go!

Text: Thank you for your help, adventurer.  We will assist you as best we can in fending off the mogu.

Text1: NO!

Text: BEHOLD! I have truly mastered the fel energies of this world! The demonic power I now command... It is indescribable, unlimited, OMNIPOTENT!

You think I've gone too far? There is no such thing. The Black Harvest will enslave the most powerful demons, draw on their power, and destroy all who oppose us, in this world, and on Azeroth! Do YOU mean to stop me, little one?
My power is unimaginable!
Hah. Your feeble attacks are entertaining. Would you like to see one of my new pets?
I'd like to see you try.
The Annihilan are incredibly destructive creatures. Their sheer strength and power is absolutely unrivaled.
WHAT?! Now you've angered me.
I'll shatter your soul!
You are nothing!
Deathwing had unstoppable power. And now, it is MINE.
You cannot stop your final Cataclysm!
This will be your END.
CATACLYSMIC POWER!
Burn.
Pure... CHAOS.
Chaos will reign.
Chaotic energy will destroy you.
The clock is ticking...
NOOOOO!
AUGHHHH!
UNFATHOMABLE!
How can it be?!
You'll burn for that.
Hold still...
This may seem meager at first, but give it a moment. Soon, the pain will be unbearable.
Twist in agony.
Rising pain.
The anguish will creep up on you.
Away from me, mongrel!
I am untouchable!
Run in fear, coward.
Destructive forces corrupt you from the inside.
Plant a seed and watch it grow...
I wonder what this seed will grow into?
I give you the gift of destruction!
Terrible destruction awaits you when this seed erupts.
Chaotic magic always has the potential for unexpected results.
Archimonde's use of the ered'ruin was brilliant. Their command of the dark energies is unparalleled.
The ered'ruin have had no master since Archimonde's death. Now I shall be that master.
While not the most powerful combatants, a pack of felhounds still has many uses.
The felhounds are always hungry for magic to devour.
If two imps are better than one imp, what's better than two imps? SIXTY IMPS.
Even the smallest demon can be valuable, in large enough numbers.

Text1: This is only what you once asked me to do if it came to this, Kanrethad. You brought this on yourself.
$n, thank you for your help. While the world will not know, you've saved them more than they're aware. Kanrethad had to be stopped. I'll see to it that he stays banished.
Kanrethad enveloped himself with so much fel energy that it corrupted him totally. But a small taste of his power should not be harmful. Go ahead.

Now go, and use what you've learned. If you ever wish to have the fel energy purged from you, or reabsorb some of Kanrethad's, talk to me. I'll be at the Altar of Damnation in Shadowmoon Valley, keeping him banished.

And now, your sad tale comes to an end.
Jubeka?! What are you...?!
...AUGHHHHHH!!!

Step forward! Witness the gift of the Thunder King!
I was chosen. My blood burns with his power!
Too much... the spirits cannot contain his might...
You will be punished! Your life a lesson in futility!
For Zandalar!!
Bar the gates. The Zandalari have failed to hold the wall.

Text: EXTREME HOZEN-FU!
Once upon a time - moments ago, in fact - a great king sought the help from a trio of powerful dwarves: The Council of Three Hammers.
The king's scouts had discovered that Zandalari trolls threatened the dwarven capital.
Surely, the king thought, if he helped them with their troll problem, they would give him more troops for his campaign against the Horde.
But what the king did not realize is that the dwarves did not trust one another!
"We cannot help you," said the Bronzebeard dwarf, "For if we turn our back on the Dark Irons, they will defeat the Wildhammer and take over Ironforge!"
"We cannot help you," said the Wildhammer dwarf. "For if we turn our back on the Dark Irons, they will defeat the Bronzebeard and take over Ironforge!"
The king was furious. "If none of you help, then Ironforge will fall under siege!"
Only one dwarf offered to help the king. "We will lend you our strength," said Moira, of the Dark Iron. "We will trust our dwarven brothers, and we will show them what loyalty means!"
And so Moira and the High King set out into the snow to save the city, leaving the others to think about their actions.
What happens next? I must know!
The High King, his champions, and the Dark Iron dwarves worked together to save Ironforge.
The other dwarven leaders were ashamed of their behavior, and vowed never again to allow fear or distrust to cloud their judgment.
And so it was a human king who helped to unite the dwarven clans so long divided.
Free to trust one another, all three dwarven leaders pledged their full strength to the Alliance cause.
Meanwhile, in the city of Orgrimmar, Warchief Garrosh Hellscream sent goblin dig teams all across the continent of Pandaria.
He promised gold and riches to any who could discover for him the hidden secrets of this land that fill Pandaria with such a dark and powerful energy.
To my surprise, his people have found something! Right here, in the sacred vale! What will happen now?
The story is still being written...
So! Even as the Alliance binds itself ever closer together, the Horde is ripping itself apart.
My friend, something is about to give. I wish I could experience the next chapter of the story, but alas, I am just the storyteller.
You, brave hero - you are strong enough to leap into the center of events as they transpire.
Go now! Go to Durotar! Make your mark as history unfurls around you!
Ah, here we are. Oh - oh, these old bones are tired. More than you can imagine.
You surprised me. I expected a hero such as yourself to balk at the task of carrying an old man up a mountain. Most are too proud.
I was going to teach you a lesson but instead, it is you who have taught me. You see, when I was young... when I was young... when I was young...
I was EMPEROR.
The realm you see all around you was mine to command.
I conquered my doubts, my fears, my anger... I buried all of it within the land.
But I held on to one vice. The one sha I never conquered. PRIDE.
My pride cloaked this land in mists! I thought we were better than the rest of the world.
I thought we could solve our own problems. But for ten thousand years, we stagnated, our doubts and fears buried in the land, rising up to fester whenever we allowed them.
Pride. It is the most insidious of sha. It is good until it is bad. And then it is more dangerous than all the others combined.
Beware of pride! Be humble! The world is plunging into chaos. Old enemies must work together. Proud races must admit they need help.
Things are going to get worse before they get better. Only by working together can we overcome the darkness.
All that stands in our way... is pride.
Tauren! What have your people done? You have dredged open a scar within our sacred Vale!
Lord Zhu, please understand - the orc "Warchief" who ordered the deed no longer speaks for the whole of the Horde. Many voices are rising up against him.
Your politics are no concern of mine. Your Horde has disrespected the sanctity of this place. You are no longer welcome here - leave at once!
Give us time, Lord Zhu. Give us the opportunity to bring Hellscream to justice.

Sunwalker, I respect your people. You have aided us in our campaign against the Sha and the Thunder King. Otherwise, I would've already ordered the Shado-Pan to purge this entire shrine. But my patience is at an end. The Horde must leave.
Please. Give us time to make this right.
Taran Zhu stares grimly into the distance.
Very well. You have until season's end. No longer.
We pandaren are no strangers to dealing with tyrants. The coming battle will try your souls. May the celestials guide your actions.
Look at us three. Back to da sands of old Durotar! It be just like old times.
Not quite, old friend. Times have changed. The line between friend and foe is not so clear.
Dey come! Hellscream tink his own people gonna roll right over.
Time ta show dis Warchief da fury of da Darkspear!
Hold! Let dem run away. Hellscream will execute dem as cowards if they go back. Sen'jin Village is safe!
Regroup! We press da advantage. Before the Warchief fortifies Razor Hill, we take it for da revolution, an' close off da road to da Barrens.
Anyone who can still fight, come wit' me!
Wait Vol'jin. Horde is spilling Horde blood. It is tearing me apart.
We need ya, mon.
I know. I trust you to lead the siege. I am needed elsewhere.
I refuse to believe that all of my brethren support Garrosh.
You set one foot in Orgrimmar, Hellscream gonna bury a knife in ya neck!
I am going to Orgrimmar, alone. Eitrigg, Saurfang, surely they are standing against Garrosh. I must find others.
I won't hear ya say such tings.
It has to be said, Vol'jin. If we do not make it through this - I want you to know. You have always been my friend. My brother.
For da Horde.
For the Horde.
Darkspear, with me! We ride! No sleep 'til Orgrimmar!
My, you are strong! When I was young, I might have doubted that we could do this. But now, I have no doubts at all.
Such wind! Such cold! Once, it would have filled these old bones with despair. But on this day, I am filled with hope.
Heh, do not get angry with the elements. Violence is their nature. I conquered my own anger long, long ago.
Such a patient one! When I was young, I would have hated this task. Nowadays, I am filled with love.
Do not fear the heights, as I did when I was young. Fear can drive us to terrible deeds. Ah, but I see that like me, you have learned the lessons of courage!
Great Jade Serpent! Hear our plea.
My champion and I seek the blessing of your wisdom.
To do what is right, no matter the cost. That is wisdom.
When is it ever wise not to act for the greater good?
I shall tear this world apart!
%s hands you a climbing rope.
It is a risk I have to take. But if I am killed, please watch over Aggra and my boy.
Look mon, Alliance filth washed up from Theramore. Kill it!
The Jade Serpent is the incarnation of wisdom in Pandaria. Let's see what she has to say.
Intruders have been spotted! Defend the Thunder Forge!
The Thunder Forge is ours!  We will defend it with our lives!
I will meet you at each of the four shrines, champion.
Remember, we must visit all four, but we only need to complete ONE of the four challenges.
Choose the challenge most appropriate for your unique talents.
Good luck!
Tell me again about the King and the Council...

Hold still demon. At this range it wouldn't take much to pierce that armor.
Ga'nar, we caught Durotan's green orc tracker that has been tracking us.
More corrupted filth. As if this scorpar infestation were not enough.
That green skin of yours marks you as the aberration you are. You are no more orc than the filth at the bottom of this pit.
Ga'nar's impatience could tear the Frostwolves apart. It is just like my brother to put his own needs above the clan.
Ga'nar! It is about time you returned. What grisly trophies are these?
I have slain the sons of the Iron Wolf. He drowns in the blood of his own.
Your fool crusade left us exposed to attack. Many died.
You are no Chieftain of mine, brother. By my rights as second son, by the justice I have dealt today, I declare mak'gora.
It has come to this.

Text: Family looks to its own! Only I cared to avenge our father's death!
Vengeance neither feeds nor protects our clan. Do you not see why father chose me as his heir when our eldest brother went missing?
Father chose wrong. This clan needs strength!
End it.
Chieftain.
Her presence defiles Frostwolf honor. The other clans will spit upon us.
Those who cannot stand... deserve... to... die! [PH - Targets Draka and is about to charge.]
Vengeance does not make our clan strong.
Rise up, brother. I need you. This clan needs you.
The strength that comes from protecting the ones you love.
We are a family, Ga'nar. Family stands together.
THAT is what makes the Frostwolves strong.
Come stand with us, brother. Join your forces with us. There is much work to be done.
I lost? How could this be?
Yes, brother. I would welcome you with open arms.
Still alive, pup? I guess I won't have to save you after all. Come, we should talk.
I am proud, but I admit you bested me, brother. I wish to learn more of your strength. We shall rejoin you.
Give me money for cool things

You'll ride the loaner. Hrah hah hah!
You have earned a place in this raid. And since you haven't yet bonded with a frostwolf of your own...
Let's see how you like the newest addition to the Warchief's arsenal... the Iron Star!
Oh, look. You're the ones that smashed up my Juggernaut.
Aggron! Show 'em who's boss!

Text1: Drek'Thar! I don't know what you are doing up there but it is angering the goren to no end.
Be careful. This place is sacred, not safe. What I am about to do could get a lot of unwanted attention.
Great spirits of the wind, heed my call! Share with me the source of your pain.
I will try to use my totems to assist you if the need arises.

Text: I came to ask the elements for aid in the coming battle.
But among the burning, biting winds of the mountains I heard the cry of the fury, Exurotus.
Beaten, half consumed, and shattered by ancient magics, the fury is the prisoner of the magnaron Kron.
The fury has been fragmented, its pieces scattered on the wind or consumed by scavengers.

Text1: Wait $p! This way. Before the giant sees you.

Text: Akama! Why not raze their town? Why give them another chance?
The word of an orc is garbage. They're only buying time.
Enough talk of battle, Hogo. Finally, Shadowmoon enjoys peace.
Or not.
MY EARS HURT!

Text1: I hear a spirit. A powerful one! Keep those goren at bay for just a little longer.
Buy me just a few more moments.
Stay down, shaman. Catch your breath. This champion can forge ahead and we will catch up when you are ready.
Spirits of the wind, lend us your speed.
The Thunderlord are fools for the most part, but they understand combat with giants.
They are also notorious for etching down their favorite tactics on armbands. I assume they are either bragging or failing to remember.
Spirits save me but it is cold. My lungs feel like they are on fire.
There it is. The carcass. I... I don't think I can go with you in there. My arm will not stop shaking and it is as if the land itself is screaming in my mind.
I will see you on the inside, $p. Spirits guide you. Orgrock, lend me a hand if you will.
In here.

Text: Our work is vital to the world.
Here! My champion arrives!
Ah, of course! My old friend from the Jade Forest!
Wait wait wait - let me make sure I get the story right.
Pandaren will tell this tale for generations!
It starts with a hero.
An outsider, from beyond the mists!
Conquering a strange new land!
Must we use the word, "Conquer?"
Venturing into forgotten vaults...
Mantid and mogu alike were brought low by the hero's fury.
Their power and wisdom seized for a greater glory!
When war came to Pandaria's shores, our hero was ready.
A faction standard-bearer, beloved by the people and feared by their foes.
Even the mighty Thunder King fell before our champion's might.
One by one the secrets of an ancient empire were laid bare.
Yes, knowledge uncovered for the benefit of the world.
POWER acquired for WAR and CONQUEST!
Let us stop for a moment - what kind of hero are we talking about?
An agent of destruction, forged by my will to forever change the face of Azeroth.
My friend, please think carefully about the legacy you will leave behind.
Behold! Latent titan power, imbued with my own draconic essence, tempered by the wisdom of the pandaren celestials.
Overwhleming power. Use it to heal or destroy! To protect or annihilate!
Come to me, champion! Collect your well-earned reward!
How will the story end?
There is only one way to find out.
A pandaren legend is born! Sing praises to our new hero, $n!
Nonsense. I had that handled. Cool as a cucumber.

Text1: I knew it. You should've stayed back at the garrison, Archmage.

Text: Tell my story...
Text1: Tell my story...

Text: I will crush it! (The Pale are the key.)
Unlike you, your minions are adorable.
I have been programmed to gloat.  Ha ha.  Ha ha.  Ha ha.
This is unfortunate.
How does that feel, $r?
If I had emotions, I still wouldn't feel sad about that.
Your minion has been terminated.
My olfactory sensors detect a burning odor.
Too bad.  Now for a real pet.
You'll pay for that.
An opportunity presents itself! I believe the Timeless Isle holds the key to unlocking the full potential of your cloak.
An island, lost in time, where the sun never sets. What could it mean?
Power! Glory! Loot!
...Ours for the taking! Hero, meet me at the Timeless Isle.
I should very much like to see this island for myself. Perhaps I will see you there?

Text1: |cFFFF8040Ki the Assassin |r|cFF71D5FF|Hspell:145427|h[Kick]|h|r|cFFFF8040s the $n.|r
|cFFFF8040Kavan the Arcanist |r|cFF71D5FF|Hspell:145530|h[Counterspell]|h|r|cFFFF8040s the $n.|r

Text: You are what you drink, $n -- I hope you have been drinking something strong.
You fought well, but your tactics are all wrong.  Have a drink and and rethink them.
Look at this, I have been beaten!  I'm going to have to brew up some ideas for next time.
Why did he fight?  To die, apparently.
The wind blows in my favor.
A fortunate attack!
I knew that was coming.
Such a glorious defeat!
Rest for now, little friend.
Maybe, uh, maybe you're ready for a lesson in chaos?
You were so preoccupied with whether or not you could win, you didn't stop to think if you should.
Gee, the lack of humility before nature that's being displayed here, uh... staggers me.
What's so great about victory? It's a violent, penetrative act that scars what it explores. What you call victory... well, nevermind.
Dead?  Don't you mean extinct?
Your pet had its shot, and nature selected it for extinction.
I'm, I'm simply saying that life, uh... didn't find a way.
That's, that's chaos theory.
What have you got on that team of yours, King Mukla?
Dinos... dropping?  Dropping?
You now face Patience!  Wisdom!  Knowledge!  What virtues do you possess, $n?
Today you have lost -- but what have you learned?
You have taught me much, $r.  It seems the master has again become the student.
A worthy sacrifice.
The autumn leaves must fall to make room for spring blossoms.
Defeat is merely a lesson masked by disappointment.
Like the stream meeting the cliff, there is beauty in the fall, if you know where to look.
To die would be a wonderfully grand adventure.
When one virtue is lost, cling to those that remain.
A worthy sacrifice?

Text1: Oh, I hope you like surprises.
You're lucky it was just your pets... this time.
In the Celestial Tournament, either you win or you die.
Take the right opponent out and it's all downhill from there.
Oh, was that one of your favorites?  My bad.
This is so easy it would be boring -- if it weren't so much fun.
You bastard, my pet may never walk again!
The things we love destroy us every time, $c, remember that.
Keep killing my pets and you may find a dash of poison in your drink tonight.
Fear cuts deeper than swords.

Text: Yer lucky Gizmo couldn't be here, but I'll still wipe the floor with ye, $c.
That one's for you, Gizmo!
Ach, so much for being good with animals. Now how do these bandages work?
Ha!  That worked better than I thought!
Oh, sorry, that fella's gunna need some tender lovin' later.
Fer a moment there, I thought we were in trouble.
No! Not again!
Curse my dwarven luck!
Oi, you'll pay for that one you will!
Do not be fooled by their diminutive size, $n, they are disciplined and quick.
Impatience is the road to defeat, you must learn to master your timing.
It requires a cunning strategist indeed to defeat my monks.  Well done, $n.
Exactly as I had planned.
You lack the necessary discipline.
Can you survive with what remains?
He fought and died with honor.
Victory often requires sacrifice.
When one Shado-Pan falls, another steps forward to take his place.
As water cracks stone, so shall we be your undoing.
The rivers foretold of this triumph.
The rivers foretold of this defeat.
And so they are washed away with little trace of what once was.
The stone thinks itself unmovable until the ground is washed away beneath it.
Cleansed by the righteous waters!
My companion is dispersed.  She will flow back to me when the time is right.
The river does not stop from a single stone.
The ebbs and flows of battle are to be expected.
Dragons are dangerous at any size, as I'm sure you'll find out.
If I can win a battle like that, I may have a chance against the Celestials.
Well done, $n.  You picked your friends wisely and led them with honor.
As I warned you before, dragons are known for their deadly attacks.
Even the strongest ally can fall to draconic magic.
A glass cannon sometimes breaks before it can fire.
You have strength I didn't see at first.
An unexpected move.
It will be difficult to recover from such a loss.
Do not despair the damage that was done here.
A long time ago, this land was beset by the shadows of doubt, of fear, and hatred.
One by one, I overcame them - and buried them deep within the earth.
And there ... they remained.
For ten thousand years ... as the veil of mists kept Pandaria hidden from prying eyes.
When the Cataclysm struck, I decided the time had come to part the mists ... and help heal our broken world.
But as your war-fleets crashed upon our shores, all of my old doubts and fears rose up, to torment the land once again.
You triumphed over the darkness I had locked away.
You have shown Pandaria the power of a true hero.
But the question still remains... why do we fight?
Face your fears. Calm your hatreds.
Find peace within yourself, so that you may share it with the world around you.
These are the greatest treasures in life.
Surely they... are worth fighting for.
I have been apprising the lorewalker of your deeds, champion. Are you ready to hear your tale?
Dear Emperor. It is done. The darkness that you once struggled against has been purged from Pandaria - forever.
But the cost... such a terrible cost.
These outsiders have brought chaos to this land. Can we trust them to set it right?

Text1: Gul'dan sends his best.

Text: I trust you have learned: To fight out of fear or anger is to fight a war that never ends.
Hehehehahahaha!
Alright, boys. Let's show 'em how Blackfuse Company fights.
BEHOLD, MY GLORIOUS DESTINY!

Text1: Sorry, vanishing!
I am sure they are trying, Kavan. Be nice.
Sooli, move!
Ah, our first enemy! Illusionary Rippers are but simple warriors. Now, let us do this!
Illusionary Flamecallers! Watch your feet, everyone. Do not stand in the lava.
I am down. Let us try again!
Oh no, did you forget to heal yourself?
The illusions will not hold back, this time. Their attacks will be relentless. Be prepared to use your strongest healing spells.

Text: Oh dear. Speedy, help!
Huh? Ohhhh, ohhh!
Ahh, Illusionary Tunnelers! Speedy and I have faced these foes before. Beware, they may burrow into the ground and then suddenly pop up under a new target, and CHOMP! Hah ha hah ha.
Argh... please... take care... of Speedy!
There is no end in sight to these illusions, but we shall hold out as long as we can.
Hah ha! Wonderful job, everyone! Friend, see Rotun about beginning the next trial.
Long ago, the Jade Serpent instructed me to purify my spirit and become one with the land, my doubts were vanquished.
When my journey began, I was reckless in my strength. The White Tiger taught me control. My hatred, anger, and violence were vanquished.
The Red Crane saw hope in me, and instructed me to look inward. Despite my visage of despair, I found this hope, and the despair was vanquished.
In the face of great fear, the Black Ox taught me fortitude. Through terror and darkness it persevered. The fear was vanquished.
You have walked the trial of wisdom, and learned of the path of the Jade Serpent. May you learn from this lesson, as I did.
You have walked the trial of strength, and learned of the path of the White Tiger. May you remember this lesson, always.
You have walked the trial of hope, and learned of the path of the Red Crane. May it guide your footsteps through time.
You have walked the trial of fortitude, and learned of the path of the Black Ox. May it bless your passage.

Text1: Help! Get these things off of me!
What are you standing in?! Get out of the fire!
Illusionary Rippers approaching. They should pose little challenge; they are but mindless grunts.
Prepare your defenses. That is an Illusionary Conqueror! When they become enraged, they gain great strength, and nothing can stop them.
A new enemy, Illusionary Flamecallers. They cast fireballs and spew lava. Use the lava to your advantage; it will burn the other illusions.
Beware! Illusionary Wind-Guards can use their wings to knock you back. When they do, they will likely switch to attacking me instead.
Illusionary Ambushers! Get their attention, quick. And get them away from me, so they cannot hit me with their devastating bananas!
Illusionary Foragers are attacking. Do not let their cute faces fool you. They can work together to cause terrible devastation.
Ahh, I cannot heal through that much damage! Did you forget to equip your heaviest armor?!
I am down. Maybe I should bring more healing herbs for next time.
Greetings. I am Sikari, master of jade lightning, chi, and healing mists. For this trial, you must protect me from the incoming illusions, while I heal you and dispatch our foes.
Greetings, again. Our next trial will be more challenging. Prepare to defend me.
Once again, you must defend me. Rotun, give us a challenge this time.
While our end is inevitable, let us try to take as many of them down with us as we can. Be ready.
Assassin!

Text: Thank you... emperor. Thank you.

Text1: Khadgar - someone's here!

Text: Rest well, honored mother. You will be avenged.
Text1: Rest well, honored mother. You will be avenged.

Text: It's all fun and games until...
Eye, what are you looking at?
Razuun, you stay here. I have other plans for... what is that?
All I require is its limitless power.
It will be done, Lord Gul'dan.
You know what needs to be done, champion.
Meet me in the Veiled Stair when the deed is done - assuming you're still alive when this is over.

Text1: Oi! That was a fun ride!
Heroes, I salute you. There's something right foul in these chambers below the city.
Ooh, that looks dangerous. Get in there, boys, and show em' what we're made of.
A right deadly machine, that is. Best watch yer step down here, heroes.

Text: Oh, ho ho... Hey now. What do we have here?
So Garrosh thinks he can cheat ol' Grizzle out of a payday, huh?!
Go get it boys, that contraption's got nothin' on real goblin engineering!
Ahhhh! Or maybe it does. I better, um, go check on the others.
I like shorts! They're perfect for this weather!
Text1: I like shorts! They're perfect for this weather!

Text: Go easy on me!
Your pet fell down!
Awww! No fair!
Yay! I'm the best!
Rise, old friends. The time has come for the next step of my plan.
Teron'gor, infiltrate the Auchenai and take control of Auchindoun. Bleed them dry.
Cho'gall, we'll finish your Frostfire business together.
I'm sending you to Nagrand to subjugate the naaru in Oshu'gun.
Hellscream!
Your attack on Karabor was cowardly and unwarranted.
What's more, we thoroughly outclassed your orcs on the battlefield.
I would be within my rights to behead you and raze this town...
...but not today.  Today, we show mercy.  Pack up your machines of war and leave this place.
Teron'gor, we'll finish your Shadowmoon business together.
I'm sending you to Talador. Infiltrate the Auchenai. Take control of Auchindoun. Bleed it dry.
Cho'gall, I'm sending you to Nagrand.
You'll subjugate the fallen naaru inside Oshu'gun.
Giselda, you stay here. I have other plans for... what is behind me?
Send word to the rest of the pack: The sons of the Iron Wolf have been found. Lok'tar ogar!
My... father... will... avenge... me.
Your father will mourn, as I have mourned.

Text1: The Iron Horde approaches. No sudden movements.
Throm-Ka, Commander Vorka. The Shadowmoon clan is honored by your presence.

Text: Shaman, women... <spits>. I have no time for seers and mystics.
Where are your true warriors? Or, is what they say about the Shadowmoon true?
That you're a mass of cravens hiding behind your magic?
Step aside, brothers. We must speak with Hellscream.
No one may enter the city. Not even you, Shaman.
Text1: No one may enter the city. Not even you, Shaman.

Text: Thrall? Varok? What business do you have here?
Strength and Honor, General. We come to speak with Garrosh. There may yet be hope for peace.
But...
Text1: But...

Text: Kor'kron! You are needed at the front!
NOW!
You know I can make no guarantee of your safety... or Garrosh's response.
Lok'tar Ogar, brothers.

Text1: Cravens? I'll show you craven!

Text: Hold. I would not spill your blood today, Hara.
You Shadowmoon are proud and still have the warriors' spirit!

Text1: <Narrows her eyes, but relaxes.>
Very well, Vorka, son of Vorash. The Shadowmoon clan will join this Iron Horde.
Lok-Regar. What orders?

Text: Gather your clan. Soon the Iron Horde will crush Karabor once and for all!

Text1: Zug-zug.
Our paths diverge here. Good luck, champion.

Text: Hatock, son of the Iron Wolf! I come for your head.
Well look here boys, the mongrel son of Garad has returned from the grave.
Hrah hrah hrah! You should have stayed dead, Ga'nar. You would have lived longer.
Had Garrad just joined the Iron Horde like he was told you would still have your precious daddy to save you today.
Chose your last words carefully Hatock. There is no Thunderlord that can stand against me.
Yes, your wolves are very formidable in battle when in the open. But let us see how you do in the shadow of a gronn.
Thunderlord...  RELEASE THE BEAST!
Keep a grip on those chains.
His arm is loosening! Tighten that slack before he puts you all against a wall.
Put your backs into it!
We have a schedule to keep.
Hatock, son of the Iron Wolf! I come for your head.
What is wrong Ga'nar? Afraid of a bit of Gronn?
I thought you Frostwolves were supposed to be skilled?
Not so easy to fight a Thunderlord, is it?
You mongrels are no match for my blade!
If you had just joined the Iron Horde I wouldn't have to kill you now.
Hatock! You cannot hide from me!
Frostwolves! Fan out and harry the Thunderlord. For vengeance!
Honored brothers and sisters! Today we achieved what Durotan would not even dare to try.
Make no mistake. We are at war. And we need a Warchief!
Those of you bold enough to stand with me - come! We will show the world the might of the Frostwolves!
We... are... FROSTWOLVES!

Text1: This is the Arbitum.
The Prophet foresaw a time in our future when our people would come into grave danger.
This shrine holds the power to save us from destruction.
I pray that the day of judgment shall never come. Power like this can only come at great cost.
Activation of The Arbitum requires an incredible amount of energy - energy of a kind that can't be found on this world.
Luckily, Iris Crystals do not originate from Draenor. We think three should be enough to supply the energy we need.
Five Iris Crystals have fallen from the skies around Shadowmoon Valley.
Unfortunately, it looks like the Shadowmoon are collecting them as well. We cannot allow them to succeed.
This is the Prophet's vision of what will come to pass.
Do you know the workings of our magic, traveler?
See this hammer? In my hands, it strikes with magical force against enemies. But used by an inexperienced trainee, it is no more than a blunt rock.
The Arbitum is only as powerful as the one who uses it.
In the right hands, it restores hope for this world. In the wrong ones, it is a weapon of absolute destruction.

Text: Spirits of the water, I seek your guidance. Spirits of the earth, I seek your strength.
I... I hear the voice of a Fury!
Fly with me, hero. We will assist them from above!
The purifying light of the naaru is both our hammer AND shield.
They are at the very temple gates - fly closer! Hurry!
Circle back. We must clear the steps.
Exarch Akama! Watch your flanks!
Thank you, old friend!
Never again will you orcish hordes darken the light of Karabor!
Press onward. By the light of the Naaru!

Text1: Watch out! Goren!

Text: Spirits of fire, I seek ferocity- aaaaaah!
Hold, $p! This is not our enemy.

Text1: Drek'Thar! $p, cover me.
Hear it faster! We are getting swarmed down here.
Let your wolf guide you Drek'Thar, and stay close to me if you can. $p, look for us in the Ice Forges when you are finished. Lok'tar ogar!
Rulkan was Ner'zhul's most trusted advisor for many years. Ner'zhul's strength and ambition guided our lives, but Rulkan's wisdom and vision inspired our spirits.
Ner'zhul's methods are brutal and direct. He cuts his enemies down by force.$B$BRulkan is clever and wise. She will turn an enemy's own blade against them.
The Shadowmoon Clan is no longer. Even if physical remnants remain, its spirit is corrupted.
We are here in self-exile. We refused to tap the magic of Ner'zhul's Dark Star.
It is unclear what will happen to us from here, but one thing is certain. My loyalty to Chieftess Rulkan is absolute.

Text: Draka, help me up. We shou- hrraarh!
Do not forget, child, one of us is blind and unable to call upon the spirits like he used to.

Text1: Bah! That should just come close to making it a fair fight. On your feet, old man.

Text: What hope is there against a foe that can consume the very elements?

Text1: You taught me long ago that the elements have always been there for us. Now it is our turn to be there for them. Victory or death, we owe it to them to try.

Text: %s rumbles in assent.
$C! You have freed my children and made me whole. Accept my boon and bring the full fury of Frostfire to your enemies.
Shaman, you alone were strong enough to hear my call. You were wise enough to know what needed to be done. Give me your totem.
Feel the flames of the fury!

Exurotus was always believed to be a legend. A story told from shaman to shaman as a symbol of a true elemental spirit.$b$bTo see something so revered in shackles is an affront to orcs, to shamanism, and to me.
The stench of tortured stone fills the air, Draka. What do you see?
I can feel hundreds of goren burrowing through the earth. This will not be easy.

Text1: Goren... lots of goren. We will distract them in order to sneak you into the Ice Forge.

Text: What you suggest should be good enough to bring down a forger, but only for a few seconds at a time.
Spirits of the wind! Heed my call! We have need of your wisdom.
This is not a place Frostwolves tread. Be mindful of what shadows you step in.

Text1: I am sworn by duty. If we are needed, we will be there. Come, Vindicators!
Hmmm... yes, you make a compelling point. Come, vindicators!

Text: Come, child. Find safe refuge in my totem.
So many? Very well. When the Prophet calls, the rangari answer. Follow me, men! Velen requests our aid!
I place my trust in Velen's wisdom. He is, after all, the Prophet of my people. Follow me, men!
It is done? Good. Once this battle is over, we will have to begin repairing Karabor's proper shield defenses.
You are a friend of the anchorites, visitor. I will see you back at the rallying point.
Carry this symbol of my gratitude into battle, and its fire shall join with your own to burn your enemies to ash.
We are the only ones close enough to collect these pieces and unleash the fury.
Your security is lax, Chieftain. I caught these Rangari spies within your gates.
They are too late. The prisoners are already on their way to Anguish Fortress.
Their blood will summon forth the Dark Star, and make me as a God among the Iron Horde!
The Warchief honors deeds, not words, shadowcaster.
Seal the exits! No draenei scum leaves this village alive!
Thunderlord... I have failed you...

Text1: Husband...

Text: Enough! You scheming draenei can keep your precious temple... for now.
The Iron Horde will return!
I will move ahead and prepare a staging area for our counter-attack.
These orcs have violated the sanctity of Karabor. Their attack ends NOW!
May the Light guide our path!
Karabor ki'le!
Karabor ki'le!
Text1: Karabor ki'le!

Text: Arepheon! Provide us with cover fire!
Rangari! Arrows ready...
FIRE AT WILL!
Artificers, disable those tanks!
As you wish, Great Prophet.
Akama, Taalo! Show them the might of the draenei!
